<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,338,1031,1057]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after Niphon Phongsuwan, my host at the Phuket Marine Biological Center.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,349,1111,1137]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Description.</emphasis>
Mature animals are 
<quantity box="[605,706,1112,1138]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 mm</quantity>
long, ~ 
<number box="[803,848,1112,1138]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="150.0">150</number>
µm wide, and the lateral sides are not enfolded (
<figureCitation box="[159,242,1152,1178]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,255,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[166,1435,182,803]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,182,803]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; photomicrographs of living specimens. A. Dorsal view of whole, strongly squeezed specimen. Double arrowhead points to male copulatory organ, arrowhead to statocyst, arrow to eyespot. B. Dorsal view of anterior end. Arrow points to ocellus. C. Dorsal view of male copulatory organ. Arrow points to eyespot, arrowhead to statocyst, double-arrowhead to male copulatory organ." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274396/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Figs. 
<number box="[227,242,1152,1178]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[279,294,1152,1178]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="5.0">5</number>
B). The length of the body is extraordinarily variable for a convolutid, depending on the state of elongation or contraction. The coloration is green due to numerous zoochlorellae, which are less densely packed at the anterior end (
<figureCitation box="[469,552,1232,1258]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,255,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[166,1435,182,803]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,182,803]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; photomicrographs of living specimens. A. Dorsal view of whole, strongly squeezed specimen. Double arrowhead points to male copulatory organ, arrowhead to statocyst, arrow to eyespot. B. Dorsal view of anterior end. Arrow points to ocellus. C. Dorsal view of male copulatory organ. Arrow points to eyespot, arrowhead to statocyst, double-arrowhead to male copulatory organ." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274396/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Figs. 
<number box="[536,552,1232,1258]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
B, 
<number box="[585,600,1232,1258]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="5.0">5</number>
A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The epidermis is entirely ciliated, with cilia that are ~ 
<number box="[835,850,1272,1298]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="6.0">6</number>
µm long. The nuclei of the epidermis are sunken beneath the body-wall musculature.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The nervous system consists of an antero-dorsal and a ventral arch of nervous tissue, two pairs of dorsal longitudinal nerve cords, one pair of ventro-lateral longitudinal nerve cords, and one pair of small and short ventral nerve cords (
<figureCitation box="[391,461,1432,1458]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,594,1601]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; reconstructions to show arrangement of organs. A. Sagittal reconstruction of whole specimen. B. Dorsal view. The gonads are paired, but for clarity, just the left testes and right ovaries are shown. C. Female and male copulatory organs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[446,461,1432,1458]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The statocyst lies 
<number box="[408,511,1472,1498]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="150.0" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="100.0">100–200</number>
µm behind the anterior tip, depending on the state of elongation or contraction of the body. The statocyst has a diameter of 
<number box="[668,697,1512,1538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="15.0">15</number>
µm, the statolith of 
<number box="[935,964,1512,1538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="10.0">10</number>
µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
A pair of orange-red ocelli lies lateral and slightly posterior to the statocyst. Each eye measures 
<number box="[1341,1356,1552,1578]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="7.0">7</number>
µm in length and 
<number box="[281,296,1592,1618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2.0">2</number>
µm in width. The lateral distance from the statocyst to each eyespot is 
<number box="[1130,1203,1592,1618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="16.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="15.0">15–18</number>
µm (
<figureCitation box="[1266,1338,1592,1618]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,255,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[166,1435,182,803]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,182,803]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; photomicrographs of living specimens. A. Dorsal view of whole, strongly squeezed specimen. Double arrowhead points to male copulatory organ, arrowhead to statocyst, arrow to eyespot. B. Dorsal view of anterior end. Arrow points to ocellus. C. Dorsal view of male copulatory organ. Arrow points to eyespot, arrowhead to statocyst, double-arrowhead to male copulatory organ." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274396/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1321,1338,1592,1618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The body-wall musculature consists predominantly of circular and longitudinal muscles and appears to be simpler than in other convolutids, at least around the genital openings (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1079,1672,1698]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,255,945,969]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,394,921]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,394,921]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; whole mounts of a specimen from population B stained with Alexa- 488 - labeled phalloidin and viewed with confocal microscopy. A. Projection of posterior part of body. Arrow points to male gonopore, arrowheads to prostatoid organs. B. Projection of ventral body-wall musculature of posterior part of body. C. Projection of penis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274399/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1063,1079,1672,1698]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Dorso-ventral muscles are densely distributed throughout the length of the body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The cyanophilic mucus gland cells are generally denser on the dorsal than on the ventral side and measure 
<number box="[151,210,1792,1818]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="7.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="5.0">5–10</number>
µm in diameter. The lateral, anterior, and posterior edges of the body are completely filled with these cells. At the anterior end they resemble a frontal organ with an orange tint, but without a terminal opening. The number of rhabdoid gland cells varies between specimens and commonly they contain a few orange rhabdoids, 
<number box="[229,273,1912,1938]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
µm long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,311,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The zoochlorellae have a diameter of 
<number box="[657,714,1952,1978]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="8.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="6.0">6–11</number>
µm and occur throughout the parenchyma (
<figureCitation box="[1249,1333,1952,1978]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,255,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[166,1435,182,803]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,182,803]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; photomicrographs of living specimens. A. Dorsal view of whole, strongly squeezed specimen. Double arrowhead points to male copulatory organ, arrowhead to statocyst, arrow to eyespot. B. Dorsal view of anterior end. Arrow points to ocellus. C. Dorsal view of male copulatory organ. Arrow points to eyespot, arrowhead to statocyst, double-arrowhead to male copulatory organ." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274396/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Figs. 
<number box="[1318,1333,1952,1978]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B, C, 
<number box="[151,166,1992,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="5.0">5</number>
A).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274396/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" targetBox="[166,1435,182,803]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,827,955]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
