</emphasis>
; photomicrographs of living specimens. A. Dorsal view of whole, strongly squeezed specimen. Double arrowhead points to male copulatory organ, arrowhead to statocyst, arrow to eyespot. B. Dorsal view of anterior end. Arrow points to ocellus. C. Dorsal view of male copulatory organ. Arrow points to eyespot, arrowhead to statocyst, double-arrowhead to male copulatory organ.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1006,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The digestive syncytium extends from halfway between the statocyst and the mouth to the female copulatory organ (
<figureCitation box="[287,357,1046,1072]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,594,1601]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; reconstructions to show arrangement of organs. A. Sagittal reconstruction of whole specimen. B. Dorsal view. The gonads are paired, but for clarity, just the left testes and right ovaries are shown. C. Female and male copulatory organs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[342,357,1046,1072]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1006,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
In mature specimens a pair of prostatoid organs occurs lateral and slightly posterior to the opening of the male genital opening (
<figureCitation box="[417,500,1126,1152]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,255,945,969]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,394,921]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,394,921]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; whole mounts of a specimen from population B stained with Alexa- 488 - labeled phalloidin and viewed with confocal microscopy. A. Projection of posterior part of body. Arrow points to male gonopore, arrowheads to prostatoid organs. B. Projection of ventral body-wall musculature of posterior part of body. C. Projection of penis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274399/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs. 
<number box="[485,500,1126,1152]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B). A prostatoid organ consists of a weak muscular bulb with a diameter of 
<number box="[151,224,1166,1192]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="27.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="25.0">25–30</number>
µm and is surrounded by prostatoid gland cells, which protrude into the bulb.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1006,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The female germinal follicles originate along the midline, extending from halfway between the statocyst and the mouth to the frontal tip of the bursal tissue (
<figureCitation box="[779,850,1246,1272]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,594,1601]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; reconstructions to show arrangement of organs. A. Sagittal reconstruction of whole specimen. B. Dorsal view. The gonads are paired, but for clarity, just the left testes and right ovaries are shown. C. Female and male copulatory organs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[835,850,1246,1272]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Those that reach the point beyond half of the length of the body have yolk granules and lipid vesicles. Only one ripe oocyte or a zygote appears at a time, and it has a diameter of ~ 
<number box="[446,491,1326,1352]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="120.0">120</number>
µm. The female opening lies 
<number box="[842,871,1326,1352]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="85.0">85</number>
µm in front of the male opening (
<figureCitation box="[1268,1348,1326,1352]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,594,1601]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; reconstructions to show arrangement of organs. A. Sagittal reconstruction of whole specimen. B. Dorsal view. The gonads are paired, but for clarity, just the left testes and right ovaries are shown. C. Female and male copulatory organs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs. 
<number box="[1334,1348,1326,1352]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[1384,1400,1326,1352]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="7.0">7</number>
B). The distal part of the vagina is ciliated. Along its whole length, the vagina is surrounded with tissue that contains numerous differently stained granules (
<figureCitation box="[675,757,1406,1432]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,594,1601]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; reconstructions to show arrangement of organs. A. Sagittal reconstruction of whole specimen. B. Dorsal view. The gonads are paired, but for clarity, just the left testes and right ovaries are shown. C. Female and male copulatory organs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs. 
<number box="[742,757,1406,1432]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C, 
<number box="[791,806,1406,1432]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="6.0">6</number>
A). The vagina opens to the seminal bursa on its caudal end, the seminal bursa has a diameter of 
<number box="[688,762,1446,1472]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="45.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="40.0">40–50</number>
µm. The bursal nozzle is slightly curved and 
<number box="[1314,1387,1446,1472]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="35.0" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="30.0">30–40</number>
µm long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1006,2032]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The paired testes lie lateral to the oocytes. Male follicles originate in a region extending from the statocyst to the female copulatory organ. Sperm accumulate to form paired false seminal vesicles, which are often distinct as far anterior as at the level of the mouth, and have in average a diameter of 
<number box="[1123,1152,1606,1632]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="25.0">25</number>
µm in front of the male copulatory organ. The false seminal vesicles converge dorsally toward an aggregation of distal tips of prostatoid gland cells, which has a diameter of 
<number box="[630,703,1686,1712]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="55.0" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="50.0">50–60</number>
µm (
<figureCitation box="[766,848,1686,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,255,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[166,1435,182,803]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,182,803]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; photomicrographs of living specimens. A. Dorsal view of whole, strongly squeezed specimen. Double arrowhead points to male copulatory organ, arrowhead to statocyst, arrow to eyespot. B. Dorsal view of anterior end. Arrow points to ocellus. C. Dorsal view of male copulatory organ. Arrow points to eyespot, arrowhead to statocyst, double-arrowhead to male copulatory organ." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274396/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs. 
<number box="[832,848,1686,1712]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C, 
<number box="[881,895,1686,1712]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
A, B, C, 
<number box="[999,1014,1686,1712]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="6.0">6</number>
A, B, C). The vesicles of the prostatoid gland cells have a diameter of 
<number box="[558,572,1726,1752]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.0">2</number>
µm. The male gonopore lies about 
<number box="[987,1031,1726,1752]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="150.0">150</number>
µm in front of the posterior end of the body, somewhat less than 
<number box="[505,549,1766,1792]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="100.0">100</number>
µm behind the female gonopore. From it a penis is invaginated, ascending caudally and touching the prostatoid gland cells with its proximal end. The penis is lined with the distal ends of mucous gland cells, which surround the copulatory organ in a star-shaped pattern (
<figureCitation box="[1166,1248,1846,1872]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,594,1601]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Convoluta niphoni sp. nov.; reconstructions to show arrangement of organs. A. Sagittal reconstruction of whole specimen. B. Dorsal view. The gonads are paired, but for clarity, just the left testes and right ovaries are shown. C. Female and male copulatory organs." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs. 
<number box="[1234,1248,1846,1872]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B, C, 
<number box="[1357,1372,1846,1872]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="6.0">6</number>
A, B, C). The copulatory organ is not enclosed in any kind of sheath.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1006,2032]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,152,538]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,1926,1952]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
While specimens from the three different populations (A, B, and C) differed in size, they were quite similar in morphology, especially of the copulatory organs (except for differences related to body size), and I consider all three to be conspecific. Animals from population A were 
<quantity box="[1040,1140,2006,2032]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 mm</quantity>
, those from population B were 
<quantity box="[216,340,152,178]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="2.3" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.6">1.6–3 mm</quantity>
, and those from population C 
<quantity box="[702,847,152,178]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="0.8999999999999999" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="0.6">0.6–1.2 mm</quantity>
. The populations in 
<collectingCountry box="[1091,1205,152,178]" name="Myanmar" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
(B and C) with the largest- and smallest-size animals are separated by just 
<quantity box="[798,875,192,218]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="km" value="10.0">10 km</quantity>
, while that in Phuket, 
<collectingCountry box="[1136,1243,192,218]" name="Thailand" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, with intermediate-size animals is ~ 
<quantity box="[390,481,232,258]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="km" value="280.0">280 km</quantity>
away. Size seems to correlate with the distribution of symbiotic algae within the body. In the smaller animals (population A and C), the symbionts are randomly distributed throughout the parenchyma; in the largest (population B) they occur just in the periphery of the parenchyma and at higher density on the dorsal side as if thickness of the body has exceeded a critical value for light transmission. The mucous glands are also distributed differently according to body size in each population. In the largest animals (population B), the gland cells are much denser dorsally but open, more or less exclusively, on the ventral side. In the smallest animals (population C), there are no gland cells on the ventral side at all, and if they protrude they do so dorsally. In this respect population A again represents an intermediate condition.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274397/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" targetBox="[151,1435,594,1601]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1625,1718]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1625,1649]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">FIGURE 5.</emphasis>
