<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1770,2036]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1436,152,218]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The placement of the species within the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[763,885,1770,1795]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[763,885,1770,1795]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Convoluta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mostly due to a lack of alternatives. Externally, the new species mostly resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Kostenko &amp; Mamkaev, 1990" authorityName="Kostenko &amp; Mamkaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[632,1254,1810,1836]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Praesagittifera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="species" species="shikoki">
<emphasis box="[632,901,1810,1835]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Praesagittifera shikoki</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kostenko" box="[910,1254,1810,1836]" pageId="8" pageNumber="16" refString="Kostenko, A. G. &amp; Mamkaev, Y. V. (1990) The position of green convoluts in the system of acoel turbellarians (Turbellaria, Acoela). 1. Simsagittifera gen. n., Zoologicheskii Zhurnal (Moscow), 69 (6), 11 - 21." type="journal article" year="1990">
Kostenko &amp; Mamkaev, 
<number box="[1193,1254,1810,1836]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1990.0">1990</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="species" species="niphoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Convoluta niphoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
doesn’t possess a saccate ciliated antrum with muscular envelopes. Some Japanese species described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yamasu" box="[189,369,1890,1916]" pageId="8" pageNumber="16" refString="Yamasu, T. (1982) Five new species of acoel flatworms from Japan, Galaxea, 1, 29 - 43." type="journal article" year="1982">
Yamasu (
<number box="[300,361,1890,1916]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1982.0">1982</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
match the general morphology of the female organs (ciliated entrance of vagina, spongy, spacious vagina, distinct seminal bursa, bursal nozzle about 
<number box="[856,885,1930,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="40.0">40</number>
µm long) and male organs (absence of muscular wall of seminal vesicle, caudally ascending penis), but none of those species has a glandular penis. Therefore, the species is placed within the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[674,796,2010,2035]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[674,796,2010,2035]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Convoluta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whose diagnosis it fits except that it lacks a seminal vesicle, but that’s also true for 
<taxonomicName authority="Yamasu, 1982" authorityName="Yamasu" authorityYear="1982" box="[515,842,152,178]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="species" species="kikaiensis">
<emphasis box="[515,665,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">C. kikaiensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Yamasu" box="[673,842,152,178]" pageId="9" pageNumber="16" refString="Yamasu, T. (1982) Five new species of acoel flatworms from Japan, Galaxea, 1, 29 - 43." type="journal article" year="1982">
Yamasu, 
<number box="[781,842,152,178]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Yamasu, 1982" authorityName="Yamasu" authorityYear="1982" box="[905,1232,152,178]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="species" species="naviculae">
<emphasis box="[905,1054,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">C. naviculae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Yamasu" box="[1062,1232,152,178]" pageId="9" pageNumber="16" refString="Yamasu, T. (1982) Five new species of acoel flatworms from Japan, Galaxea, 1, 29 - 43." type="journal article" year="1982">
Yamasu, 
<number box="[1170,1232,152,178]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Another distinction is the relative simplicity of the body-wall musculature, especially the lack of crossover muscles.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/274398/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" targetBox="[151,1435,262,1266]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1291,1419]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1291,1315]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[287,485,1292,1315]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="species" species="niphoni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[287,485,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<taxonomicName box="[287,398,1292,1315]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Convoluta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="genus">Convoluta</taxonomicName>
niphoni
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[492,577,1291,1315]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,577,1291,1315]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
; photomicrographs of histological sections stained with hematoxylin. A. Sagittal section through posterior part of body. B. Detail of male copulatory organ in A. C. Cross section through male copulatory organ. Note distinct cell walls. Arrows point to algal symbionts, arrowheads to spongy tissue containing granules and surrounding the vagina, double-arrowheads to distal part of gland cells.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1470,1776]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
I was able to observe copulation in several instances among animals from populations A and C. In this behavior, animals slowly approach each other, either from opposite directions or one from behind the other. They touch each other slowly, especially with the anterior end. The worms then lay their ventral sides together (remaining in contact with the Petri dish on one lateral side), facing in opposite directions, and, bringing their genital openings in position, they embrace each other, forming a double spiral. In this position the pair spins for from 
<number box="[257,353,1670,1696]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="40.0" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="20.0">20 to 60</number>
seconds. After this time, they undo the embrace and crawl away, one animal often dragging the other for some time. 
<taxonomicName authority="Costello &amp; Costello, 1938" authorityName="Costello &amp; Costello" authorityYear="1938" box="[452,1073,1710,1736]" class="Acoelomorpha" family="Convolutidae" genus="Polychoerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acoela" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Xenacoelomorpha" rank="species" species="carmelensis">
<emphasis box="[452,748,1711,1736]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Polychoerus carmelensis</emphasis>
Costello &amp; Costello, 
<number box="[1014,1073,1710,1736]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="1938.0">1938</number>
</taxonomicName>
copulates in a similar fashion (
<bibRefCitation author="Costello" box="[159,479,1750,1776]" pageId="9" pageNumber="16" refString="Costello, H. M. &amp; Costello, D. P (1938 b) Copulation in the acoelous turbellarian Polychoerus carmelensis. Biological Bulletin, 1, 85 - 98." type="journal article" year="1938" yearSuffix="b">
Costello &amp; Costello 
<number box="[401,463,1750,1776]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="1938.0">1938</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
